Et repentel, “ and then suddenly.’' Et connecting the third member of a series is very common in the Annals (see Intr. 61).— pavebant terrebantquel. “they feared and inspired fear.” We have here a striking word-picture, drawn in outline by a few bold strokes. Notice the grave solemnity of the passage, and how the effect is heightened by the omission of conjunctions, auxiliary verba, and all unnecessary words—quibuscum . . . toleravisset} Tibe· rius had served in Pannonia during his first consulship. — apud pa- tresl, “before the fathers‚’' i.e. in the senate—quem . . . caseth “which ought (par esset) to be kept. without participation in (exper- tem) neither the favor nor the severity.'’ i.e. the senate should be consulted, and decide whether their request should be granted or refused, and thus share in the favor or odium of the decision.

26. Quae persennia, “what he should present.'' The conditions which he proceeds to present are the same as those named in sec. 17. As the relative implies ea (“ such as ''), the subjunctive is used (H. 501). —cum =. . . obtenderetl, “ when he interposed the will of the senate and of his father.’' The imperf. subj. here, as usual, with cum in a temporal sense, follows an historical pres. in the principal clause (H. 518, II.).—nunquam nisi ad sel, “nowhere except to them-
